
HTML attributes provide additional information about HTML elements. They are always included in the opening tag of an element and usually come in name-value pairs like name="value". Attributes help define properties or behaviors of HTML elements.

Key Points about HTML Attributes:
Placed in Opening Tag: Attributes are always added to the opening tag of an element.
Name-Value Pair: Most attributes come in name-value pairs, separated by an equals sign (=). The value is typically enclosed in quotes.
Global vs. Specific Attributes: Some attributes are global (applicable to all HTML elements), while others are specific to certain tags.

Commonly Used HTML Attributes:

1. Global Attributes
Global attributes can be applied to any HTML element.

class: Specifies one or more class names for an element. Classes are used to apply CSS styles and for JavaScript manipulation.


<div class="container"></div>
id: Specifies a unique identifier for an element. IDs are used for CSS styling, JavaScript, and anchoring links.


<h1 id="main-title">Hello World</h1>
style: Specifies inline CSS styles for an element.


<p style="color:blue;">This is a blue text.</p>
title: Provides additional information about an element, usually displayed as a tooltip when the mouse hovers over the element.


<abbr title="Hypertext Markup Language">HTML</abbr>
lang: Declares the language of the elementâ€™s content.


<p lang="en">This is in English.</p>
data-*: Custom data attributes used to store extra information that can be accessed via JavaScript.


<div data-user-id="12345"></div>
hidden: Hides the element from view, but it remains in the DOM.

<div hidden>This will not be visible.</div>
tabindex: Specifies the tab order of an element when navigating with the keyboard.


<input type="text" tabindex="1">
accesskey: Specifies a shortcut key to activate or focus an element.


<button accesskey="s">Submit</button>
draggable: Specifies whether an element is draggable.

<img src="image.jpg" draggable="true">
  
2. Specific Attributes
These attributes are specific to certain HTML elements.

src (Source): Specifies the URL of the media file (image, video, audio, etc.).

Used with: <img>, <script>, <iframe>, <audio>, <video>, <source>
  
<img src="image.jpg" alt="An image">
alt (Alternative Text): Provides alternative text for an image, useful for accessibility.

Used with: <img>

<img src="image.jpg" alt="A description of the image">
href (Hyperlink Reference): Specifies the URL of the page the link goes to.

Used with: <a>, <link>

<a href="https://www.example.com">Visit Example</a>
target: Specifies where to open the linked document.

Used with: <a>, <form>

<a href="https://www.example.com" target="_blank">Open in a new tab</a>
rel (Relationship): Specifies the relationship between the current document and the linked document.

Used with: <a>, <link>

<a href="https://www.example.com" rel="noopener noreferrer">Visit Example</a>
action: Defines the URL to which the form data is sent when submitted.

Used with: <form>

<form action="/submit-form" method="post">
method: Specifies the HTTP method to use when submitting the form.

Used with: <form>

<form action="/submit-form" method="post">
type: Specifies the type of element or input.

Used with: <input>, <button>, <script>, <link>, <style>, <embed>, etc.

<input type="text" name="username">
value: Defines the initial value of an input element.

Used with: <input>, <button>, <option>, <li>, etc.

<input type="submit" value="Submit">
placeholder: Provides a short hint that describes the expected value of an input field.

Used with: <input>, <textarea>

<input type="text" placeholder="Enter your name">
checked: Indicates whether an input of type checkbox or radio is checked.

Used with: <input type="checkbox">, <input type="radio">

<input type="checkbox" checked>
readonly: Specifies that an input field is read-only.

Used with: <input>, <textarea>
  
<input type="text" value="Read-only" readonly>
disabled: Disables an element, making it unclickable and not submitted with the form.

Used with: <input>, <button>, <select>, <textarea>, etc.

<button disabled>Submit</button>
multiple: Allows the selection of multiple options in a form element.

Used with: <select>, <input type="file">

<select multiple>
  <option value="1">Option 1</option>
  <option value="2">Option 2</option>
</select>
size: Specifies the visible number of options in a drop-down list or the width of an input field.

Used with: <input>, <select>
<select size="4">
  <option value="1">Option 1</option>
  <option value="2">Option 2</option>
</select>
min / max: Specifies the minimum and maximum values for an input field.

Used with: <input type="number">, <input type="date">, etc.

<input type="number" min="1" max="10">
step: Specifies the legal number intervals for an input field.

Used with: <input type="number">, <input type="range">, etc.

<input type="number" step="0.5">
srcset: Specifies a set of images to use based on different conditions (like screen resolution).

Used with: <img>

<img src="small.jpg" srcset="large.jpg 2x" alt="A responsive image">
autoplay: Specifies that the media will start playing as soon as it is ready.

Used with: <audio>, <video>
<video src="video.mp4" autopla
  y></video>
controls: Displays controls (like play/pause) for the media element.

Used with: <audio>, <video>
  
<video src="video.mp4" controls></video>
loop: Specifies that the media should start playing again from the beginning when it finishes.

Used with: <audio>, <video>

<audio src="audio.mp3" loop></audio>
